name: Cañon de la Virgen
description:
Cañon de la Virgen is one of the prettiest canyons in the Dominican Republic. It is indeed a true slot with no hope of escape once you enter. The slot is dark inside. Waterproof headlights are recommended.

Tourists sometimes hike up to the waterfall at the end of the slot. Confusingly, the locals, and the internet, label this waterfall Cueva de la Virgen. It's not a cave - it's a canyon. If you tell locals you are going to Cañon de la Virgen, they will probably correct you and tell you it's called Cueva de la Virgen. Truth is, only one known local has ever entered the slot. All other descents (maybe five groups EVER as of February 2022?) have been by capitaleños, an American and a Mexican.

The canyon is spring-fed and limestone. It flows all year, with flows higher in the wet seasons. It can be run all year, though the dry season seems ideal.

It's not a very difficult or technical canyon. Rappels are bolted, and several small drops can be overcome with teamwork and pack-anchors. The biggest hazard in this canyon is probably giant centipedes. The Barahona area seems to have more giant centipedes than anywhere else in the country, and you're likely to see several in this slot and the jungle on the approach. Don't get bit!

All in all, this is a fun canyon, the first one documented in these mountains. If you're looking to get to know these mountains and do some first descents, of which there are many awaiting, start with Cañon de la Virgen.

Approach

The approach is relatively straightforward along a road with the final part in the forest. A GPS is essential, as there are a bunch of side trails and dirt roads, and no signs. It's all in dense forest, so it's hard to pinpoint using satellite maps. You may find yourself asking a local at some point.

With a high clearance vehicle (or by paying mototaxis), drive up the dirt road from the highway to Estancia Don Armando. You may safely park your car at the Estancia. They charge around 200 pesos (February 2022) for parking. If your vehicle is not high clearance and/or you reach a point on the road where you can't proceed further, park off the road and walk the rest of the way. Do not leave any valuables in the vehicle. In 2023 the road was in good condition all the way to Estancia Don Armando.

If the road is very bad, you can leave the vehicle near the highway and walk the whole way. It's recommended to ask in a nearby house for them to watch your car for the day, and offer a small fee.

The dirt road will bring you to Estancia Don Armando. It's a good idea to say hi to the local family at the ranch, just to let them know you're doing the canyon, as they own the land. They are friendly. Even if walking from the highway, it may help to give them maybe 100 pesos per canyoneer.

Just past the Estancia, turn left onto a dirt road. Follow this dirt road up a gentle gradient. Just when it starts to make a hard right, turn left and leave the road to start a thick bushwhack down the steep slope to the canyon. There is no established trail here yet. You may wish to handline or even rappel a few of the small (<10 m) cliffs. The rock is extremely sharp.

This bushwhack is brief and will deposit you at the start of the slot. You've arrived.

Alternatively, if your group is feeling energetic and you'd like a longer day (the normal route only takes a little more than 2 hours), you can hike further up the road another 1.3mi and drop in the drainage down a clearcut hillside. This will add about 2.5 hours of dry non-technical canyon upstream of the first rappel; dry except for one pool in the middle -- debatable about whether to suit up or not for it. Plus 45min walking up the road, which is much steeper than the first part. Follow the .kml map on this page for details.


Descent

If you entered the canyon at the correct location, you should be entering just above a confluence. Suit up and get your harnesses on when you hit the water. You'll go through a small, extremely pretty pool, and then see a side canyon that comes in on canyon-right, above a ledge. This canyon is unexplored and likely a good one.

Head downcanyon! You'll walk under a huge boulder just before the first rappel, of 5 meters. This rappel is not bolted. Meat-anchor, then partner assist or pack anchor. Jumping not recommmended, unless flow is high. In high flow, be careful of possible hydraulics.

Rappel 2 is less than 5 meters into a nice pool.

{{pic|downcanyon.jpg ~ Looking downcanyon from Rappel 

2}}

Rappel 3 is another short one down a light waterfall into a pool.

After Rappel 3 is the bat section. It's dark, covered in guano, and filled with huge bats flying around. There are hundreds of almond fruits floating in the water.

Next is an anchorless rappel (Rappel 5) into a deep pothole. Use a handline, or carefully slide this one.

Immediately after the pothole is Rappel 5. You'll have to reach the anchor on the left side, and rappel around 10 meters down the travertine formation into a near-dark enclave.

After Rappel 5 is a shallow curve and then Rappel 6, the final rappel. Rappel 6 has a bolt that you can rig to traverse out to the rappel. The rappel is then around 12 meters over a lip, down a waterfall, and into a stunning pool.

After the last rappel is a downclimb on a sketchy wooden ladder made of logs. The canyon then opens. You may take off your wetsuits and gear here and exit.

Exit

From the canyon's end, follow the trail back down along the stream to your vehicle. The trail is easy to follow. If in doubt, you can follow the water tubing all the way back to the dirt road.

Red tape

There are no permits required. The landowners may or may not ask you for a few dollars to pass. The land around this canyon, even the jungle, is indeed owned by local families, so it's fair that they ask for some money. What is not wanted is that this canyon becomes a major tourist attraction, which is the stated goals of some locals.

Locals will push you to use a guide. Using a guide is wholly unnecessary if you have this page's beta and are experienced. If you do want a guide to help you get to the put-in, but not take you down the canyon, contact Johan (Spanish-speaking only) on WhatsApp at 1(829)860 9436.

Locals may tell you there have been some assaults and break-ins near the trail. The area feels very safe, as there are only a few families around that own the land. These claims may be falsified to encourage you to use a guide. Or they may be real, so go at you own risk. We had no problems whatsoever.

Beta sites

Trip reports and media

https://www.lukaseddy.com/canyons-of-the-dominican-republic


Background

This canyon first descended by a French team, likely between 2000 and 2020. They bolted the route. Since then, only a few groups appear to have ever run it.

The route was first independently descended by Lukas and Suhei Eddy, who then documented it on this page. Dominican canyoneers (all five or six of them...) also believe that canyons should be free and open to all, but Dominican outdoors culture in general seems to espouse needing a guide for EVERYTHING even if you are an experienced canyoneer with solid beta and a GPS. An experienced canyoneer with this page's beta should have no problem on this route.

Please be kind and respectful to locals, and you won't have any problems.
